ng trends of employment in wartime America have opened up new jobs for such women as this young East Liverpool, Ohio, girl who has pioneered in two new fields since graduation from high school. She learned butchering first, and built up quite a reputation as a purveyor of choice cuts. Now she's one of the most efficient service station attendants in the neighborhood. Her name? Virginia Excell", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2017693667/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/2020655689", "http://www.loc.gov/item/2020655689/", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/c832ea60-9aa6-5bd8-abb3-d260a755ba56", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_mv01", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_mv/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_sr01/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_ph/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_ms02/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_ms01/", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/afc2018030.afc2018030_05081_mv01"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["occupational folklife project", "nafziger, mark", "mcgriff, meredith a. e."], "date": "2018", "dates": ["2018"], "description": ["Mark Nafziger, the owner of Brush Creek Pottery, discusses his work as a potter. The pottery is part of Sauder Village, a tourist attraction which houses a number of craftspeople making both historical and contemporary objects. Mark talks about his education, the establishment of Brush Creek Pottery, his relationship with others at Sauder Village, the development of his production line, some of the changes the business has gone through over the years, and the equipment and processes he uses."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-01-31T20:11:15.128Z", "group": ["catalog-split-11", "catalog", "afc/2018030", "main-catalog-split-11", "production-potters"], "hassegments": true, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/2020655689/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/afc/afc2018030/afc2018030_05081/afc2018030_05081_mv.jpg", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:afc:afc2018030:afc2018030_05081:afc2018030_05081_ph:afc2018030_05081_ph01/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg#h=246&w=370", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:afc:afc2018030:afc2018030_05081:afc2018030_05081_ph:afc2018030_05081_ph01/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=493&w=740", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:afc:afc2018030:afc2018030_05081:afc2018030_05081_ph:afc2018030_05081_ph01/full/pct:25/0/default.jpg#h=986&w=1480", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:afc:afc2018030:afc2018030_05081:afc2018030_05081_ph:afc2018030_05081_ph01/full/pct:50/0/default.jpg#h=1973&w=2960", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:afc:afc2018030:afc2018030_05081:afc2018030_05081_ph:afc2018030_05081_ph01/full/pct:100/0/default.jpg#h=3947&w=5920"], "index": 8, "language": ["english"], "location": ["middle west", "ohio", "archbold", "united states"], "mime_type": ["image/jpeg", "image/jp2", "audio/mp3", "video/mp4", "audio/wav", "application/pdf", "application/x-video", "application/x-audio"], "number": ["2026-01-21t22:52:08.900000", "online resource", "2020655689", "2023-11-14t08:43:20"], "online_format": ["image", "audio", "video", "pdf"], "original_format": ["film, video", "sound recording"], "partof": ["occupational folklife project", "catalog", "american folklife center", "production potters of the midwest: archie green fellows project, 2018-2019"], "score": 22.959343, "shelf_id": "http://lccn.loc.gov/2020655689", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["potters", "interviews", "personal narratives", "ohio", "united states", "material culture", "pottery craft", "technological innovations", "art pottery", "oral histories", "folklore", "sound recordings", "middle west", "artists' studios", "color", "pottery industry", "video recordings", "self-employed", "digital photographs", "nafziger, mark"], "timestamp": "2026-01-31T21:04:46.792Z", "title": "Mark Nafziger interview conducted by Meredith McGriff, 2018-10-22", "type": ["moving image"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2020655689/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/2020655686", "http://www.loc.gov/item/2020655686/", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/b5e47792-aeaf-55fb-b2a3-1ff980e4f680", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_mv01", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_mv/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_sr01/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_sr02/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_ph/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_ms01/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_ms02/", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/afc2018030.afc2018030_04440_mv01"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["mcgriff, meredith a. e.", "occupational folklife project", "blue, robert", "galloway, susan blue"], "date": "2018", "dates": ["2018"], "description": ["Husband and wife Robert Blue and Susan Galloway discuss their work as potters. Topics include (in order): their shared studio; their educations; how they got interested in pottery; Susan teaching ceramics at McHenry County College; Bob selling work at art fairs; starting the Clay Workers Guild of Illinois; raising a family; collaborating with neighbors on a yearly festival; the types of pottery they work on together; ways they work separately; possibly retiring; and appreciation of having a partner."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-01-31T20:11:04.971Z", "group": ["catalog-split-08", "catalog", "afc/2018030", "main-catalog-split-08", "production-potters"], "hassegments": true, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/2020655686/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/afc/afc2018030/afc2018030_04440/afc2018030_04440_mv.jpg", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/servic